{{Infobox person |name = Eivind Kristofer Reiten |image = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1953|04|02|df=yes}} |birth_place = |other_names = |known_for = Member of the [[Centre Party (Norway)|Centre Party of Norway]], Former [[Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Fisheries]] and [[Minister of Petroleum and Energy (Norway)|Minister of Petroleum and Energy]] |occupation = Chairman of [[Norske Skog]] |nationality = [[Norway|Norwegian]] }}
'''Eivind Kristofer Reiten''' (born 2 April 1953) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] economist, [[corporate officer]] and [[politician]] for the [[Centre Party (Norway)|Centre Party]]. He was a [[Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Fisheries]] and [[Minister of Petroleum and Energy (Norway)|Minister of Petroleum and Energy]] during the 1980s, before entering a career in business. Reiten served as the Director General (CEO) of [[Norsk Hydro]] between 2001 and 2009, after which he took up the chairmanship of [[Norske Skog]]. Eivind Reiten was also Chairman of [[StatoilHydro]] for four days, until he resigned from his position after [[Norsk Hydro]] had been accused of corruption.
==Political career== Reiten was born in [[Midsund]] as the son of Kristofer Reiten, a farmer and fisher, and housewife Kjellaug Opstad. He enrolled as a student in 1972, and graduated from the [[University of Oslo]] in 1978 with a [[Cand.oecon.|degree]] in economics. He worked as a civil servant from 1979 to 1982, and as a secretary for the Centre Party from 1982 to 1983. He was then brought into the government as [[state Secretary (Norway)|state secretary]] to the [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]] from 1983 to 1985. He then became [[Minister of Fisheries and Coastal Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Fisheries]] from 1985 to 1986 as part of the [[Second cabinet Willoch]], and [[Minister of Petroleum and Energy (Norway)|Minister of Petroleum and Energy]] from 1989 to 1990 as part of [[Cabinet Syse]].<ref name=bio>{{stortingetbio|EIRE}}. Retrieved on 6 December 2008.</ref> In his last political position, he was responsible for the deregulation of the electricity market in Norway.<ref name=sparrebjorndal>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.no/forsiden/naringsliv/article1195359.ece |title= - Det er veldig bittert |author=Sparre, Martin Riber |author2=Bjørndal, Bente |work=[[Dagens Næringsliv]] |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Having chaired the [[Centre Youth]], the youth wing of the Centre Party, from 1979 to 1981, he served as a deputy representative to the [[Storting|Norwegian Parliament]] from 1985 to 1989.<ref name=bio/>
==Business career== Reiten started working for [[Norsk Hydro]] in 1988, heading the energy division from that year, and becoming senior vice president of special projects in 1991. From 1992 he led the refining and marketing division, and from 1998 the aluminum division. He was appointed executive vice president for light metals in 1999. He succeeded [[Egil Myklebust]] as chief executive officer in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hydro.com/en/Persons/Eivind-Reiten/ |title=Eivind Reiten |author=[[Norsk Hydro]] |date=27 August 2007 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101141638/http://www.hydro.com/en/Persons/Eivind-Reiten/ |archivedate=1 January 2009 |df= }}</ref> He was a member of the board of the [[Norges Bank|Bank of Norway]] from 1991 to 1994 and [[Norske Skog]]industrier from 1997 to 2000, and has [[chair (official)|chaired]] the board of [[Posten Norge|Norway Post]] (1996–1999) and [[Telenor]] (2000–2001).<ref name=bio/> He has attended the [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] meetings.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} He is a fellow of the [[Norwegian Academy of Technological Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntva.no/index.php?option=com_club&view=member&id=362%3Areiten-eivind-kristofer&Itemid=60|title=Medlemmer: REITEN, Eivind Kristofer|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Technological Sciences]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref>
===Libya corruption case=== As part of the merger between [[Statoil]] and the oil and gas division of Norsk Hydro, Reiten was appointed [[chair (official)|chair]] of the merged [[StatoilHydro]] that merged on 1 October 2007. Four days later Reiten withdrew from the seat.<ref name=sparrebjorndal /> The reason was that it was uncertain whether or not he knew about a corruption case Hydro had been accused of, where a [[Libya]]n consulting company and the consultant Abdurrazag Gammudi had been paid {{NOK|60 million}}, used to make bribes, after the Hydro take-over of [[Saga Petroleum]] in 1999. Stated Reiten, it was in no-one's interest that he retain a conflict of interest by retaining the seat of chair in the company that would investigate himself. The case had arisen on 26 September, after a Hydro employee had leaked information about the matter; it had not been identified as part of the [[due diligence]] performed by Statoil prior to the merger.<ref name=sparrebjorndal /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.no/energi/article1192587.ece |title=Alt om Libyasaken |author=Bjerke, Espen |work=[[Dagens Næringsliv]] |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> He was replaced by his deputy, [[Marit Arnstad]], who is also a former Minister of Petroleum and Energy from the Centre Party.<ref name=sparrebjorndal /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dn.no/energi/article1195400.ece |title=- Marit Arnstad ny StatoilHydro-leder |author=Bjerke, Espen |work=[[Dagens Næringsliv]] |date=4 October 2007 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> The investigation from StatoilHydro concluded that Reiten was informed about this during 2000 and 2001, while the investigation in Norsk Hydro concluded that Reiten did not know about the corruption.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.auraavis.no/meninger/leder/article3884051.ece |title=Hydrosjefen for fall? |author=[[Aure Avis]] |date=9 October 2008 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref> Since the Norsk Hydro investigation—that included checking 1.5 million documents—could not show that Reiten knew about the corruption, Hydro Chairman [[Terje Vareberg]] confirmed that Reiten would not be removed from his position. However, two executives of StatoilHydro were required to leave immediately.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nrk.no/nyheter/okonomi/1.6251536 |title=Eivind Reiten blir sittende |author=Sættem, Johan B. |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=7 October 2008 |accessdate=4 December 2008 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>
===Leaving Norsk Hydro=== In January 2009 Reiten announced that he was stepping down as Chief Executive of Norsk Hydro from 30 March 2009, with executive vice president [[Svein Richard Brandtzæg]] taking over.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Hydro Chief Reiten steps down |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/content/view/21477/1/ | agency =[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] |work=Norway Post |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=13 January 2009 }}</ref> Reiten has since been nominated to replace Kim Wahl as Chairman of [[Norske Skog]] at the company's [[annual general meeting]] in April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/oilRpt/idUKOSN00191220090206|title=Norske Skog nominates Eivind Reiten as chairman|last=Stoltz|first=Aasa Christine|date=6 February 2009|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=2009-02-07}}</ref>
==Personal life== Reiten is married and has two children.<ref name=sparrebjorndal /> He resides in [[Oslo]].
