{{Italic title}} {{Speciesbox | name = Red phantom tetra | image = Megalamphodussweglesi01.jpg | taxon = Hyphessobrycon sweglesi | authority = ([[Jacques Géry|Géry]], 1961) }}
'''''Hyphessobrycon sweglesi''''' is a [[species]] of [[tetra]] that lives in the [[Orinoco River]] [[drainage basin]] in [[South America]].<ref name="FishBase">{{cite web|url=http://www.fishbase.org/summary/speciessummary.php?id=10659 |title=''Hyphessobrycon sweglesi'' (Géry, 1961) Red phantom tetra |accessdate=2009-11-05 |work=[[FishBase]]}}</ref> The fish has a round black spot behind the [[gill|gill-plate]], a black band on the [[dorsal fin]] that is bordered above and below by creamy-white. The other fins are red same as the upper rim of the eye.<ref>{{cite book | last = McInerny | first = Derek | authorlink = |author2=Geoffry Gerard | title = All About Tropical Fish |edition=4th | publisher = Harrap Limited | year = 1989 | location = Great Britain | pages = 248 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-8160-2168-6 }}</ref> The fish eats [[worm]]s, small [[insect]]s, and [[crustacean]]s.<ref name="FishBase"/> The species can lay up to 400 eggs that can hatch in a day and that are susceptible to [[fungus]]. The species' appearance is very similar to ''[[Hyphessobrycon megalopterus]]'' (black phantom tetra). The species' [[scientific name]] used to be ''Megalamphodus sweglisi'' and the species' [[common name]] is '''red phantom tetra'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tropicalfishandaquariums.com/Tetras/RedPhantomTetra.asp |title=Red Phantom Tetra Information |accessdate=2009-11-05 |work=Tropical Fish Aquariums}}</ref>
== Aquarium care == It is recommended to keep a mixed group (males and female) of at least 8–10 specimens in a tank no smaller than 20 US gallons (76 L).
