'''Mesotrophic soils''' are [[soil]]s with a moderate inherent [[Fertility (soil)|fertility]]. An indicator of soil fertility is its [[base (chemistry)|base]] status, which is expressed as a ratio relating the major [[Plant nutrition|nutrient]] [[Ion#Ions|cations]] ([[calcium]], [[magnesium]], [[potassium]] and [[sodium]]) found there to the soil's [[clay]] percentage. This is commonly expressed in hundredths of a [[Mole (unit)|mole]] of cations per [[kilogram]] of clay, i.e. cmol (+) kg<sup>−1</sup> clay.

